@startuml agent-finalizer-pvc
' Agent deletion: pvcRetention is implemented by editing the ownership graph before releasing the object.
' Source of truth: docs/src/controller/finalizers.md
!include _style.puml

start
:delete Agent requested;<<$extBg>>
:apiserver sets deletionTimestamp.
kaalm.io/agent-finalizer blocks the
delete; the object stays readable;

if (does a Pod exist?) then (yes)
  :send SIGTERM, wait up to\nterminationGracePeriodSeconds;
else (no)
  :nothing to terminate: Hibernated,
  Pending before Pod creation, or
  Failed before the first Pod started;<<$mutedBg>>
endif

if (was the PVC provisioned\nby Kaalm?) then (no)
  :spec.persistence.existingClaim was
  never given an ownerRef, so it is
  untouched under either setting;<<$mutedBg>>
  :remove the finalizer;
  :apiserver deletes the Agent;
  stop
else (yes: it carries an ownerRef to the Agent)
endif

if (AgentClass.spec.persistence.pvcRetention?) then (Retain)
  :Patch the PVC to STRIP its ownerRef;<<$storeBg>>
  :remove the finalizer;
  :apiserver deletes the Agent;
  :cascade GC finds no owner:\nthe PVC survives;<<$storeBg>>
  stop
else (Delete, the default)
  :leave the ownerRef intact;
  :remove the finalizer;
  :apiserver deletes the Agent;
  :cascade GC removes the PVC\nalongside the Agent;<<$mutedBg>>
  stop
endif

note right
  Ordering hazard: the ownerRef edit
  must land BEFORE the finalizer is
  removed. Once the finalizer entry
  is gone the object can vanish at
  any moment, taking the PVC with it.
  ....
  pvcRetention governs the PVC's fate
  when the Agent is deleted. It is
  distinct from, and independent of,
  PersistentVolume
  .persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy,
  which governs the PV's fate when
  the PVC is deleted.
end note

@enduml
